## ✅ Recommended: Option A — Cloudflare Tunnel

This is the best approach for your situation. It gives you a **real public HTTPS URL** while keeping the backend on your machine where it can access everything.

### How It Works

```mermaid
graph LR
    A["🌐 Browser<br/>Anyone on the Internet"] -->|HTTPS| B["☁️ Cloudflare Edge<br/>ng-sentra.yourdomain.com"]
    B -->|Encrypted Tunnel| C["🖥️ Your Windows PC<br/>cloudflared daemon"]
    C -->|localhost:3000| D["⚡ NG-SENTRA Server<br/>Express + tRPC + Vite"]
    D -->|SSH:22| E["🖧 VirtualBox VM<br/>192.168.1.14"]
    D -->|HTTPS:9200| F["🔍 Wazuh/Elastic<br/>192.168.1.14:9200"]
    D -->|MySQL/TLS| G["🗄️ TiDB Cloud<br/>gateway05.tidbcloud.com"]
```

**Traffic flow:**
1. User visits `https://ng-sentra.yourdomain.com`
2. Cloudflare routes the request through an encrypted tunnel to your PC
3. Your PC runs the full NG-SENTRA server on `localhost:3000`
4. The server can access your VirtualBox VM, Wazuh, and everything on your local network
5. Response goes back through the tunnel → Cloudflare → user's browser

### Step-by-Step Setup

#### Step 1: Install `cloudflared` on Windows
```powershell
# Option A: Using winget (recommended)
winget install --id Cloudflare.cloudflared

# Option B: Download from https://developers.cloudflare.com/cloudflare-one/connections/connect-networks/downloads/
```

#### Step 2: Quick Test (No account needed!)
```powershell
# This gives you a temporary public URL instantly - no signup required
cloudflared tunnel --url http://localhost:3000
```
This will output something like:
```
Your quick Tunnel has been created! Visit it at:
https://random-words-here.trycloudflare.com
```
You can share that URL with anyone and they'll see your NG-SENTRA dashboard!

#### Step 3: Permanent Setup (Free Cloudflare account)
For a persistent, named URL:
1. Create a free account at [dash.cloudflare.com](https://dash.cloudflare.com) (no credit card)
2. Add a domain (you can get a free `.eu.org` or `.pp.ua` domain, or use any domain you own)
3. Create a named tunnel:
```powershell
cloudflared tunnel login
cloudflared tunnel create ng-sentra
cloudflared tunnel route dns ng-sentra ng-sentra.yourdomain.com
```
4. Create config file at `~/.cloudflared/config.yml`:
```yaml
tunnel: <your-tunnel-id>
credentials-file: C:\Users\ZIAD\.cloudflared\<tunnel-id>.json

ingress:
  - hostname: ng-sentra.yourdomain.com
    service: http://localhost:3000
  - service: http_status:404
```
5. Run as a Windows service (auto-starts on boot):
```powershell
cloudflared service install
```

### What You Need To Do Before Deployment

> [!NOTE]
> The codebase is **already 100% ready**. No code changes are needed. You just need to:

1. Build the production version: `pnpm build`
2. Start the server: `npm run start`
3. Run cloudflared alongside it

